WKB approximation for  and
 of a very massive field 


Obtaining the exact solution of Eq. () is a very
complicated problem. However, it can be solved iteratively if
there is a small parameter of the considered task.

Let us evaluate the order of terms in this equation. If  the
characteristic scale of variation of the gravitational field is
designated as :
              L^-1 = 
       1/r,  [ (fr^2) ]'  , 
        [ (fr^2) ]"  ^1/2 , 
        [ (fr^2) ]"'  ^1/3 , 
       ,
       then in case , one can consider the quantity
            _WKB  =  L 1
      as a small parameter of the iterative procedure. In this case as
the zeroth-order term of the iterative procedure one can choose
              (W^2)_(0)  = ^2+f r^2  l (l+1)+f m^2.
       The term of the next order [the iteration procedure demands the
using of  instead of  in the right hand side of
Eq. () for calculation of the next order term]
            (W^2)_(2)  =f 4 r^2 +V+
      f' 8   (W^2)_(0)  ' (W^2)_(0)  
      +f 4  (W^2)_(0)  " (W^2)_(0)  
      -5f 16  (W^2)_(0)  ' ^2 (W^2)_(0)  ^2 
      has the order ,
i.e., for all values of  and  this term is much less than
the zeroth-order term. For derivation it is convenient to choose
as the zeroth-order term of the iterative procedure the following:
              (W^2)_(0)  = ^2+f r^2 
       (l+12)^2+f m^2,
       because the addition to  some of the addends from
 does not change the conclusions:
            (W^2)_(0)  (W^2)_(2)  (W^2)_(4)        or
             (W^2)_(2)  ^ 2 _WKB  
       (W^2)_(0) , (W^2)_(4)         ^ 4 _WKB   (W^2)_(0) ,
             and
            W^2=(W^2)_(0) +(W^2)_(2) +(W^2)_(4) +.
      This approach gives (Ref.) the DeWitt-Schwinger
expansions of  and 
 in terms of powers of . Note that
there are the different methods of derivation of the
approximations for  and 
 in the large mass limit.


